Soccer Statistics with R Shiny

Nyaosi Mogaka

2022-09-28

Motivation

I have always had a fascination around sports data, and using frequencies or quantitative assessments to support observations within sports. With this growing trend, I decided to build this shiny app to allow me to present this type of information.

The Data

How I collected the data for this app is beyond the scope of this post, you can however check out this tool by Ben Torvaney that allows for the collection of event match data. The structure of the dataset is as seen below:

str(df)

MatchID represents an id for different matches that are played. A full football match is played in two halves with a break in the middle of the game, Period therefore represents either the 1st or 2nd half/period of the football match TeamID is almost self-explanatory because a football match is played by two opposing sides/teams. The PlayerID is self-explanatory as well, representing a player in a team that is represented by 11 players each at a time. Type represents the event category taking place at a specific time in the match, while Event is a descriptor of the event category and Result is the outcome of the event. Time is a timestamp of the event on the match video, while X, Y, X2, Y2 represent the start and stop coordinate points for an event.

Summarizing The Data

After getting this dataset, a match summary was the initial information I hoped to get from it. This is information similar to that which is typical in a referees report, information I had mentioned earlier like bookings, substitutions and goals. Build I/O Components

For the shiny app, I wanted to get the quantitative assessments for a player from a specific game, and so I narrowed down my Inputs and Outputs to the following:

Inputs

The shiny app shall have three drop-down inputs that will act as filters on the dataset.Each drop down shall filter the data sequentially, with the first filter being by MatchID , followed by Team, then PlayerID. This should look like this.



Outputs

Once the data has been filtered, we can then use it to present the user with information by using summary tables and plots. Some of the outputs are shown below;
